```json
{
  "application": "Slurm",
  "details": {
    "resources": {
      "memory": "246GB",
      "nodes": 32,
      "tasks_per_node": 6,
      "cpus_per_task": 1,
      "partition": "cpu",
      "account": "bcfx-delta-cpu",
      "job_name": "th_new/hmg_ldc3d",
      "time": "2:00:00",
      "constraint": "scratch"
    },
    "modules": {
      "gcc": "11.4.0",
      "openmpi": "4.1.6"
    },
    "environment": {
      "OMP_NUM_THREADS": 1,
      "GCC_PATH": "/sw/spack/deltas11-2023-03/apps/linux-rhel8-x86_64/gcc-8.5.0/gcc-11.4.0-yycklku",
      "OMPI_PATH": "/sw/spack/deltas11-2023-03/apps/linux-rhel8-zen3/gcc-11.4.0/openmpi-4.1.6-lranp74",
      "LIBSTDC": "/sw/spack/deltas11-2023-03/apps/linux-rhel8-x86_64/gcc-8.5.0/gcc-11.4.0-yycklku/lib64",
      "PATH": "/sw/spack/deltas11-2023-03/apps/linux-rhel8-x86_64/gcc-8.5.0/gcc-11.4.0-yycklku/bin:/sw/spack/deltas11-2023-03/apps/linux-rhel8-zen3/gcc-11.4.0/openmpi-4.1.6-lranp74/bin:/usr/local/bin:/usr/bin:/bin:/usr/local/sbin:/usr/sbin:/sbin",
      "LD_LIBRARY_PATH": "/sw/spack/deltas11-2023-03/apps/linux-rhel8-x86_64/gcc-8.5.0/gcc-11.4.0-yycklku/lib64:/sw/spack/deltas11-2023-03/apps/linux-rhel8-x86_64/gcc-8.5.0/gcc-11.4.0-yycklku/lib:/sw/spack/deltas11-2023-03/apps/linux-rhel8-zen3/gcc-11.4.0/openmpi-4.1.6-lranp74/lib:/usr/local/lib64:/usr/lib64:/usr/lib/x86_64-linux-gnu:/usr/lib/gcc/x86_64-linux-gnu/11/:/usr/lib/gcc/x86_64-linux-gnu/11/lib64:/lib64:/lib/x86_64-linux-gnu:/lib/i386-linux-gnu",

```

This script is running within the **Slurm** workload manager. It requests a substantial amount of resources including 246 GB of memory, 32 nodes, 6 tasks per node, and 1 CPU per task. The script utilizes the "cpu" partition, uses the "bcfx-delta-cpu" account, and has a job name of "th_new/hmg_ldc3d". The script also specifies a job time limit of 2 hours and requires a constraint of "scratch."

The script loads specific versions of GCC and OpenMPI modules, configures environment variables for these modules, and sets the `FI_CXI_RX_MATCH_MODE` environment variable to "software". Finally, it runs a Python script named "solver.py".
